How to produce a new Radian release

# Fetch latest code
git pull

# Verify it
On Mac OS X:
	Open the XCode project
	Build -> Clean
	Build -> Build
	Open a terminal and cd into the Radian directory
	Run the script ./check and make sure it succeeds
On Linux:
	cd radian/linux
	make clean && make
	cd .. && ./check

# Update the --version string
In the beginning of compiler/main/radian.cpp, look for #define VERSION
Change the text of this macro to "X.Y.Z" for the appropriate version number

# Update the version number in CHANGES
The first line in the CHANGES file should say "not yet released". Replace this
with a string of the form "X.Y.Z - DD Month YYYY".

# Commit changes to the version strings
git commit -a

# Tag your commit
git tag X.Y.Z

# Push the version number update and your new tag
git push origin --tags

# Make binary distribution
Make a directory named "radian-X.Y.Z-processor-system"
The "processor" string should be "x86_64" or "i386"
The "system" string should be "macosx" or "linux-gnu"
Into this directory, copy these items, recursively:
	CHANGES
	README
	COPYING
	radian
	library/
tar cf radian-X.Y.Z-processor-system.tar radian-X.Y.Z-processor-system
gzip radian-X.Y.Z-processor-system.tar

# Push to web server
Make a new directory: /pub/X.Y.Z/
Upload radian-X.Y.Z-processor-system.tar.gz into this directory
Edit /download page:
	Move the old download link under "Older versions"
	Update the "current version" to reflect the new version number
	Point the download link to /pub/X.Y.Z/radian-X.Y.Z-processor-system.tar.gz
	
# Announce the new version
Copy the latest section of the CHANGES file into a new blog post
Title the blog post "Release X.Y.Z"
Convert the change entries into bullet items in an unordered list
Wrap all names, keywords, and code snippets in <code/> 
